ife and death become a continuity and a boundlessness that white supremacy and neoliberalism cannot interdict. By charting a course of black life in Mpondoland, Canham tells a story of blackness on the African continent and beyond.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award Recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzSouth AfricazPondoland. 0aPondo (African people)xHistory. 0aPondo (African people)xSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024224?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024224/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles